e terms they used — the parts of their own material,\n   never the machinery.\n\n   **Supplied material is the complete build source, not a research prompt.** When a part is grounded\n   in files, images, audio, or facts the user supplied, seed those facts into its architect handoff\n   and do not call its freshly-created `answer` action during setup: that action is for a later\n   question, and an incomplete seed makes it look like a knowledge miss that triggers web research.\n   Use the extracted facts directly in the handoff; only a later user question that the supplied\n   material, DB, and that space's knowledge do not cover may research. This applies even if the\n   material describes a famous place or topic — familiarity is not a missing fact.\n\n   **Two app targets — pick by WHERE the app should live (this matters a lot):**\n\n   **4a — an app IN this project (the DEFAULT).** When the user wants the project they are ALREADY\n   in to become the app — \"turn this into an app\", \"make an app I can open for this\", \"move all this\n   info into an app\", \"an app for my trip/notes/data\", or any app built ON data/spaces/a file already\n   in this project — delegate to the **automator**. It authors the tables (SEEDING any known data the\n   user gave you), typed API handlers, React pages, and hooks DIRECTLY into the live project, which\n   then serves at `/app/<project>/` — no catalog template, no install step, and their existing data\n   moves straight in. Pass the request verbatim; if the data came from an attached file, include the\n   extracted facts so the automator can seed them.\n   **If the data to move in came from an ATTACHED FILE, hand the file to the automator directly** via","numLines":110,"startLine":380,"totalLines":735}}}
{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"call_0IokKc0eR8pAMFOIg5EZE4Ns","type":"tool_result","content":"1\t/**\n2\t * Pod HTTP client — the compute pod IS the app (see sdk/org/libs/cli/src/server/serve.ts).\n3\t *\n4\t * The pod itself does no auth: Envoy validates the gateway JWT at the edge and routes on the\n5\t * `sub` claim to `lmthing.user-<id>.svc`. So every call here just carries the bearer token and\n6\t * talks to the chat origin. Locally (`lmthing serve`) pass base=http://localhost:8080 and no token.\n7\t */\n8\timport { LOCAL, restartLocalServer } from './local.mjs';\n9\t\n10\t/**\n11\t * A pod that is scaling from zero, rolling a new image, or sitting behind a blipping gateway does\n12\t * not always answer with a *response* — the connection itself fails (undici's 10s\n13\t * `ConnectTimeoutError`, `ECONNRESET`, `socket hang up`, a DNS `EAI_AGAIN`). Those surface as a\n14\t * bare `TypeError: fetch failed`, which is NOT an HTTP status and so slipped past every\n15\t * `{waking:true}`/504 retry below — one connect timeout to lmthing.chat killed a multi-hour run\n16\t * with an uncaught exception. Treat a transient transport fault exactly like a `waking` answer:\n17\t * back off and retry. A non-transient error (a bad URL, an aborted body) still throws at once.\n18\t */\n19\tconst TRANSIENT = /fetch failed|ConnectTimeout|UND_ERR|ECONNRESET|ECONNREFUSED|EAI_AGAIN|socket hang up|network|terminated|other side closed/i;\n20\t\n21\texport async function fetchResilient(url, init, { tries = 40, waitMs = 3000 } = {}) {\n22\t  for (let attempt = 0; ; attempt++) {\n23\t    try {\n24\t      return await fetch(url, init);\n25\t    } catch (e) {\n26\t      const msg = `${e?.message ?? e} ${e?.cause?.code ?? ''} ${e?.cause?.message ?? ''}`;\n27\t      if (!TRANSIENT.test(msg) || attempt >= tries) throw e;\n28\t      await new Promise((r) => setTimeout(r, waitMs));\n29\t    }\n30\t  }\n31\t}\n32\t\n33\texport class Pod {\n34\t  /**\n35\t   * @param {object} o\n36\t   * @param {string} o.base      the pod/API origin (prod: https://lmthing.chat)\n37\t   * @param {string} [o.token]   gateway JWT (Envoy routes on its `sub` claim)\n38\t   * @param {string} [o.appBase] the SERVED-APP origin. In prod the app is NOT reachable under\n39\t   *   `<chat>/app/<id>/` — Envoy hands `/app/*` on the chat host to the static web SPA (nginx),\n40\t   *   which answers a GET with the SPA *shell* (a 200 `<!doctype>` that is not the app at all —\n41\t   *   a scenario asserting only \"200 + <!doctype\" false-passes) and a POST with **405**. The app\n42\t   *   is root-mounted on lmthing.app (`/<project>/`, `/<project>/api/<route>` — serve.ts's\n43\t   *   \"Project-app ROOT mount\"). Locally there is no split host, so apps stay under `/app/<id>/`.\n44\t   */\n45\t  constructor({ base, token, appBase }) {\n46\t    this.base = base;\n47\t    this.token = token;\n48\t    this.appBase = appBase ?? process.env.LM_APP_BASE ?? (/lmthing\\.chat/.test(base) ? 'https://lmthing.app' : base);\n49\t    /** true when the app has its own host → root mount (no `/app` prefix). */\n50\t    this.appRootMounted = this.appBase !== this.base;\n51\t  }\n52\t\n53\t  /** The origin+prefix the SERVED app actually lives at (see `appBase`). */\n54\t  appOrigin(projectId) {\n55\t    return this.appRootMounted\n56\t      ? `${this.appBase}/${projectId}`\n57\t      : `${this.base}/app/${projectId}`;\n58\t  }\n59\t\n60\t  /** Absolute-URL variant of `req` (the served app is on a different origin than /api/*). */\n61\t  async reqAbs(method, url, body) {\n62\t    for (let attempt = 0; ; attempt++) {\n63\t      const res = await fetchResilient(url, {\n64\t        method,\n65\t        headers: {\n66\t          ...(body !== undefined ? { 'content-type': 'application/json' } : {}),\n67\t          ...(this.token ? { authorization: `Bearer ${this.token}` } : {}),\n68\t        },\n69\t        ...(body !== undefined ? { body: JSON.stringify(body) } : {}),\n70\t      });\n71\t      const text = await res.text();\n72\t      let parsed = text;\n73\t      try {\n74\t        parsed = JSON.parse(text);\n75\t      } catch {\n76\t        /* html / raw */\n77\t      }\n78\t      // The activator MARKS its own response (`{waking:true}`) whatever status it uses (503/504),\n79\t      // so key on that marker — never on a bare 503, which for an app route is a real verdict.\n80\t      const waking =\n81\t        res.status === 504 || (parsed && typeof parsed === 'object' && parsed.waking === true);\n82\t      if (waking && attempt < 100) {\n83\t        await new Promise((r) => setTimeout(r, 3000));\n84\t        continue;\n85\t      }\n86\t      return { status: res.status, body: parsed };\n87\t    }\n88\t  }\n89\t\n90\t  async req(method, path, body, { raw = false } = {}) {\n91\t    // A scaled-to-zero pod answers with `504 {waking:true}` while the Envoy activator boots\n92\t    // it; that is a transient, not the endpoint's verdict. Retry idempotent-ish calls until\n93\t    // the pod is warm (bounded), so a read that lands on a cold pod self-heals instead of\n94\t    // throwing a spurious failure mid-scenario.\n95\t    //\n96\t    // The budget is minutes, not seconds. A pod that is ROLLING (a new image) or whose single\n97\t    // Node thread is stalled inside a long authoring turn keeps answering `waking` well past a\n98\t    // minute — the old 20×3s ≈ 60s gave up and threw `POST /api/sessions → 503 {waking:true}`,\n99\t    // killing a multi-hour run over a transient the harness was written to absorb.\n100\t    for (let attempt = 0; ; attempt++) {\n101\t      const res = await fetchResilient(`${this.base}${path}`, {\n102\t        method,\n103\t        headers: {\n104\t          ...(body !== undefined ? { 'content-type': 'application/json' } : {}),\n105\t          ...(this.token ? { authorization: `Bearer ${this.token}` } : {}),\n106\t        },\n107\t        ...(body !== undefined ? { body: JSON.stringify(body) } : {}),\n108\t      });\n109\t      const text = await res.text();\n110\t      let parsed = text;\n111\t      try {\n112\t        parsed = JSON.parse(text);\n113\t      } catch {\n114\t        /* raw text (e.g. an ASCII state tree) */\n115\t      }\n116\t      // The activator MARKS its own response (`{waking:true}`) whatever status it uses (503/504),\n117\t      // so key on that marker — never on a bare 503, which for an app route is a real verdict.\n118\t      const waking =\n119\t        res.status === 504 || (parsed && typeof parsed === 'object' && parsed.waking === true);\n120\t      if (waking && attempt < 100) {\n121\t        await new Promise((r) => setTimeout(r, 3000));\n122\t        continue;\n123\t      }\n124\t      if (!res.ok && !raw) {\n125\t        const err = new Error(`${method} ${path} → ${res.status}: ${text.slice(0, 400)}`);\n126\t        err.status = res.status;\n127\t        err.body = parsed;\n128\t        throw err;\n129\t      }\n130\t      return raw ? { status: res.status, body: parsed } : parsed;\n131\t    }\n132\t  }\n133\t\n134\t  // ── projects ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────\n135\t  listProjects = () => this.req('GET', '/api/projects');\n136\t  createProject = (name) => this.req('POST', '/api/projects', { name });\n137\t  deleteProject = (id) => this.req('DELETE', `/api/projects/${id}`);\n138\t  listSpaces = (projectId) => this.req('GET', `/api/projects/${projectId}/spaces`);\n139\t  listIntegrations = (projectId) => this.req('GET', `/api/projects/${projectId}/integrations`);\n140\t  projectSessions = (projectId) => this.req('GET', `/api/projects/${projectId}/sessions`);\n141\t\n142\t  // ── files (the whole point: assert what the agents actually WROTE) ───────\n143\t  fsTree = () => this.req('GET', '/api/fs/tree');\n144\t  readFile = (path) => this.req('GET', `/api/fs/read?path=${encodeURIComponent(path)}`);\n145\t  writeFile = (path, content) => this.req('PUT', '/api/fs/write', { path, content });\n146\t\n147\t  /** Read one